'''''Mazogs''''' is a maze video game developed by [[Don Priestley]] and published for the [[ZX81]] by [[Bug-Byte]] in 1982. It was subsequently licensed by Softsync and published in the US for the [[Timex Sinclair 1000]].<ref name='pcw17mar83'>{{cite magazine |title=Softly, softly|magazine=Popular Computing Weekly|issue=11|publisher=Sunshine Publications|date=17 March 1983|page=66|url=https://spectrumcomputing.co.uk/page.php?issue_id=2746&page=11|access-date=13 January 2023}}</ref>

Don Priestley followed up the game with ''[[Maziacs]]'' for the [[ZX Spectrum]].

==Reception==
Dick Olney for ''[[Personal Computer World]]'' said "Overall, this is undoubtably one of the best games of its type which I've played on the ZX81.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.org/details/PersonalComputerWorld1982-08|title=Personal Computer World (1982-08)|date=August 1, 1982|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>

Arthur B. Hunkins for ''[[Compute!]]'' said "Mazogs is an excellent, single-player, treasure/maze game [...] Its full screen graphics make excellent use of the Sinclair/Timex capability."<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.org/details/1983-02-compute-magazine|title=Compute! Magazine Issue 033|date=February 1, 1983|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>

Fred Blechman for ''[[Electronic Fun with Computers & Games]]'' said "Highly recommended - unless you already have high blood pressure."<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.org/details/Electronic_Fun_with_Computer_Games_Vol_01_No_09_1983-07_Fun_Games_Publishing_US|title=Electronic Fun with Computer & Games - Vol 01 No 09 (1983-07)(Fun & Games Publishing)(US)|date=July 1, 1983|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>

